SIMPLE: incarnate
RECORDS: 4

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Incarnate
<hw>In*car"nate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Pref.
<ets>in-</ets> not + <ets>carnate</ets>.]</ety> <def>Not in the flesh;
spiritual.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I fear nothing . . . that devil carnate or <qex>incarnate</qex>
can fairly do.</q> <rj><qau>Richardson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Incarnate</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Incarnate
<hw>In*car"nate</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>incarnatus</ets>, p.
p. of <ets>incarnare</ets> to incarnate, pref. <ets>in-</ets> in +
<ets>caro</ets>, <ets>carnis</ets>, flesh. See
<er>Carnal</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>Invested with flesh; embodied in a human nature and
form; united with, or having, a human body.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Here shalt thou sit <qex>incarnate</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He represents the emperor and his wife as two devils
<qex>incarnate</qex>, sent into the world for the destruction of
mankind.</q> <rj><qau>Jortin.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Flesh-colored; rosy; red.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Holland.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Incarnate</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Incarnate
<hw>In*car"nate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Incarnated</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Incarnating</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <def>To
clothe with flesh; to embody in flesh; to invest, as spirits, ideals,
etc., with a human from or nature.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>This essence to <qex>incarnate</qex> and imbrute,⟦br⟧
That to the height of deity aspired.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Incarnate</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Incarnate
<hw>In*car"nate</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To form flesh; to granulate,
as a wound.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>My uncle Toby's wound was nearly well -- 't was just beginning to
<qex>incarnate</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Sterne.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Incarnation</ent>⟦br⟧
